content:
Drunken millers force monks to dance. Millers are enticed
to monastery and beaten. Italian Novella: Rotunda.

Baker cannot understand how a man who has been a miller can be a beggar. It is
a wonder that the farmers are not beggars instead. Wesselski Bebel I 118 No. 3.
child:
If he had been like the rest of the congregation he would
have become rich. Pauli (ed. Bolte) No. 825.

content:
A mad dog in place of a miller in a sack. Flemish: DeMeyer FFC XXXVII 84 No.
27b.

Pauli (ed. Bolte) No. 785; Fb “møller” II 649; Italian Novella:
*Rotunda.

Butcher wonders that man who has been buying his meat for
seven years can still be alive.

Ugly cobbler continually threatens to throw his last at
people.

The object of jokes. Spanish:
Boggs FFC XC 98 No. 836D*.

Shoemaker drinks more than his portion of “drink of lies”,
which has been prepared for all to partake of equally.
Wienert FFC LVI 39; Halm Aesop No. 136.

child: Client flees when cobwebs are brought in to medicate cuts.
Barber uses cut hair to staunch cuts.
Talkativeness of the fishwives of Paris.

Anecdotes of their
invective. Nouvelles Récréations No. 63.
Devils annoyed at their noisy trade. Flemish: DeMeyer FFC XXXVII 84 No. 27a.

content: Tailors cowards as warriors: go home to their needles.

**B. Salditt Hessische
Blätter f. Vksk. XXX--XXXI 88.

Sews the stolen piece of cloth on the outside of his coat,
thinking that it is on the inside. Type 2005*.
child: Thievish tailor cuts a piece of his own coat.

Thieving tailor can hide stolen cloth even in
needle-and-thread tube.

Man chased by bear to camp claims that he brought it in
thus since he did not want to carry it.

content: Cohabitation between lunatics brought about for sport.
Only prostitutes can carry the corpse of a prostitute.

Begging cripples hurry away from shrine lest they be healed
and lose their livelihood.

Custom not to bury dead
until someone has something good to say about him. No one will praise a dead
usurer until a barber is willing to say that he had a good beard. *Pauli (ed.
Bolte) No. 195; Wesselski Mönchslatein 122 No. 105.

Devil will not carry usurers to hell but will drag them by
the legs.

So declares a youth paid by a
usurer to protest against the priest’s remarks that the devil would carry all
usurers off. Pauli (ed. Bolte) No. 191; cf. Spanish: Espinosa Jr. No. 213.

The parson asks the various trades and professions to rise one by one for a
special blessing. When he calls for the usurers none reply. Pauli (ed. Bolte)
Nos. 193, 194; Crane Vitry 207 No. 179; Scala Celi 168b No. 959; Alphabet No.
792.
Only usurers can carry the corpse of the usurer.

It refuses to be moved
by anyone else. (Cf. †X521.) Pauli (ed. Bolte) No. 190; Irish: Beal XXI 326,
cf. O‘Suilleabhain 74.

Usurer encourages sermons against usury, so that his
competitors will cease activity.

child: Man heeds what he thinks to be call to the ministry.
Young man plowing corn sees letters “P.

C.” formed by clouds. He explains situation to minister,
asks to be ordained. The minister explains that the letters mean “plow corn”
instead of “preach Christ”. U.S.: Baughman.

Eloquent lawyer makes obviously guilty client doubt his own
guilt.

content: Lawyer loses tongue in death because he sold it in life.

The dying man has the lawyer and the notary stand on
either side of him. U.S.: Baughman; Spanish: Boggs FFC XC 134 No. 1583*.

Cock crows at church and the sexton awakes and begins to
sing.
The parson has no need to preach.
Those who know may teach those who don‘t know. *Type 1826.
child: No need to give sermon about saint again.

“Last year I told you all about his life and works. He has
performed no new miracles.” *Wesselski Arlotto I 188 No. 8; Italian Novella:
Rotunda.

content:
Refuses to say, “I’m not worthy” at communion. Italian
Novella: Rotunda.
Guilty of everything connected with the seven senses.

When the priest to whom he is confessing says there are
but five senses, the magistrate says that he needs two more senses than other
people. Pauli (ed. Bolte) No. 297.

Crane Vitry 149f. No. 39; Scala Celi 7b No. 48; Herbert
III 77 No. 200, 462 No. 94, 497 No. 238, 499 No. 262; Alphabet No. 41; Mensa
Philosophica No. 147.
child: Crane Vitry 150 No. 40; Scala Celi 7b No. 45; Mensa Philosophica No. 148.

content:
Foreigner wonders why city with so many judges has not been
destroyed.

Bell breaks and priest‘s patron whistles in place of ringing the bell at mass.
*Wesselski Arlotto I 187 No. 7.
The dream: all parsons in hell.

The smith tells the parson whom he has summoned that he
has dreamed of going to heaven where St. Peter would not admit him before he
saw a parson. There were no parsons in heaven, but all in hell. *Type 1738.
child:
Devout woman and a priest retell their dreams. The priest has dreamed
that all the devout women are to be found in hell. Lithuanian: Balys Index No.
1847*.

content: Enmity between priests and monks: chickens and eggs.

Monks eat eggs and make chickens expensive; priests eat
hens and make eggs high. Pauli (ed. Bolte) No. 69.

Beggar frightens lawyer into giving by telling him of all
the lawyers in hell.

Spanish: Boggs FFC XC
95 No. 819*; cf. U.S.: Baughman.

At the blessing of the grave the parson’s ox breaks loose:
“Now the devil has him.”
The corpse with his feet cut off.

The coffin-maker has fitted him to the coffin. The parson:
“On the last day he will arise.” One of the coffin-makers: “Did I say that?”
Type 1699*.
The parson who said there is no devil.

The bear-showman lets the bear climb up the pulpit. The
parson thinks the bear is the devil. Type 1745*.

A sexton hears thieves in the cemetery cracking nuts and
thinks it is the devil cracking bones. With the gouty parson on his back he
comes upon the thieves who, thinking it is their companion with the sheep, call
out, “Is he fat?” The sexton: “Fat or lean, here he is!” *Type 1791; *BP III
395; *Pauli (ed. Bolte) No. 82; Scala Celi 101b No. 547; Alphabet No. 333;
U.S., England: *Baughman; Lithuanian: Balys Index No. 1791, Legends No. 889.
child:
Robbers mistake man for devil (the “sheep” speaks, “Gently,
gently!”).

content: A bad year for priests: few funerals.

All but the priest rejoice over the good health of the
community. He bemoans his loss of income from burials. *Wesselski Arlotto II
248 No. 155.

If his son were only a fool he would let him study to be a
priest.
Tame bear tied to church bells.
Chapel endowed with fifty blows for the friar.

Lawyer thrown back into mud when rescuers learn that he is
a lawyer.

Parson intones instructions to the sexton (cook) as a part
of the mass. *Type 1831; Spanish: Boggs FFC XC 147 No. 1831A*.
child:
Rector confesses his sacristan: “Have you drunk the wine designated for the
mass?” -- “I can‘t hear you.” Exchange of places. Sacristan asks rector: “Have
you kissed my wife?” -- “Really, I can’t hear you.” Lithuanian: Balys Index No.
2451*; Rumanian: Schullerus FFC LXXVIII No. 1777*.

content:
One-eyed parson in dimly lighted church joins the wrong
couples.

Marries the old man to the girl
and the old woman to the boy. Italian Novella: *Rotunda.

child:
Fortune-teller shows others how to get rich but remains
poor himself.
(Cf. †J1062.) Herbert III 22 No. 186; Crane Vitry 250 No. 266.

content: Parson refreshes himself during the sermon.
child: Parson takes a drink of liquor during the sermon.
Parson takes a chew of tobacco during the sermon.

content: Nero has reserved place in hell for lawyers.
Crane Vitry 148 No. 36; Spanish Exempla: Keller.
Master of seven liberal arts begs from wagoner.

With his one art latter supports his family. Pauli (ed.
Bolte) No. 855.
What will happen when there are so many lawyers.

Woman sees the crowds of students in the law school. She
knows that the one lawyer in her village has ruined nearly everyone. *Pauli
(ed. Bolte) No. 787; *Wesselski Bebel I 216 No. 110.

child:
Bishop willing to admit castrated man as monk: wishes all
were in the same condition.

content:
Makes a present application of the words of the parson.
*Type 1833; U.S.: Baughman.
child:
Variants: (a) What evil did Adam do?--He (shoemaker) made
my shoes too small. (b) What kind of man was Moses? He was a day laborer. *Type
1833A; *Wesselski Arlotto II 233 No. 113.

Parson “Where did the father stay?”--“He stayed to hold the
oxen.”

Parson: Where was Christ when he was neither in heaven nor
on earth?--He was in the willow-grove looking for a stick to beat those who ask
foolish questions.
Names of persons in the Trinity.

The priest‘s example: the three cows. The boy: “The Holy
Ghost has just had a calf.” Type 1833D; England: Baughman.

A boy rides with a rich man. Goes into church and leaves his
coat lying on the sled. When the parson preaches about the rich man who went to
hell, the boy calls out, “Then he took my coat along!” *Type 1832.

content: Lawyer who tries to practice without lying fails.

He wants to show how Christ rode into Jerusalem. Sexton
sticks ox with needle. *Type 1786.

Locked in church all week by mistake. When the congregation comes, the hog runs
between the parson’s legs and carries him out. *Type 1838; Fb “svin”.

Parson preaches so that half the congregation weeps and
half laughs.

Has clothes torn in the back.
Those that see this laugh. He wins the wager. *Type 1828*; Wesselski Morlini
297 No. 44.
Parson smears his hand with butter.

Rascals have spread butter on the altarbread. The parson
preaches, “What is the life of man?” and therewith brings his hand down on the
altar-bread: “Pure butter!” Type 1836*.
Parson put to flight during his sermon.
child:
Sexton’s dog steals sausage from parson‘s pocket: parson
flees.

Sexton puts needle in sacramental bread: parson sticks his
hand.
Sexton arranges wasp-nest so that parson sits on it.

content:
Music teacher charges double for those who have taken music
before.

One fee for teaching and one for
making them forget the old teaching. Pauli (ed. Bolte) No. 314.
The parson sings like a goat.

The parson sees an old woman weeping and believes that she
is touched by his singing. When spoken to she says that she has been reminded
of her old goat which she has lost. *Type 1834; Wesselski Hodscha Nasreddin II
243 No. 539; *Crane Vitry 157 No. 56; *Pauli (ed. Bolte) No. 576; Fb “prædiken” II 882; Scala Celi 25a No. 164;--Italian Novella:
Rotunda; India: Thompson-Balys.
The parson put out of countenance.
child: The large loaves need a large oven.

Parson says that the loaves with which Jesus fed the
people in the wilderness were as large as the mountains. The mason asks what
kind of oven they were baked in. Type 1834*.

The
parson asks the boy: “What does your father say when you begin to eat?” Boy:
“You young devil, etc.” *Type 1841.
Doctor cures palpitation of heart: patient stops breathing.
Head cut off to cure snakebite.

Eyedrops prescribed for stomach ache so that patient can
see what he eats.

Man with cheeks stuffed with food operated on to remove
swellings.

Doctor called to attend sick man immediately gives orders
for the funeral.

content: Parson is to let a dove fly in the church.
The hungry parson and the porridge-pot.

Overnight at the peasant‘s house. The hungry parson hunts
the porridge in the dark, guided by a rope the sexton has given him. Series of
accidents. *Type 1775; Fb “seng” III 187a.
child:
Stupid man tries to take honey from jug at night while
visiting.

content:
A youth promises to marry an old maid if she will sit all
night on the roof.

She falls down. Type
1479*; Russian: Andrejev No. 1479*.

On one side is a bundle of straw (her husband) and on the other a dog (her
child). She gives the straw bundle a push and thereupon falls on the floor
herself. Type 1480*.

X751. †X751. Marriage forbidden
outside the parish. An order is read in church forbidding the young people to
marry girls from other parishes. *Type 1475.
The mother trains the old maid to speak properly.
The wolf steals the old maid.
She keeps him for a husband. Type 1477.

One
of the old maid‘s three teeth breaks off. Type 1478.

Lie: remarkable actions of big fish.

Roast pigs run around with knife and fork in back ready for
eating.
Lie: roast hens fly, heads to sky, tails to ground.

Horse takes cattle out to pasture; brings them in by
himself.
Trained horse as harvester and hunter.

He rolls in the field.
Oats in his flanks; club in his tail kills birds. (First ed. †X921.3.) (Cf.
†X1252.1.) Type 1892.

(First ed. †X1021.1.)
U.S.: *Baughman, *Folk-Say I 62 (bibliography of “Paul Bunyan” stories).

Man plows through stump which catches the back of his pants
in cleft.

His oxen continue to pull; he
holds onto the plow, pulls the stump out of the ground. U.S.: *Baughman.
Lie: large boar has bristles as long as pitchfork tines.

England, Scotland: *Baughman; Lithuanian: Balys Index No.
1879*.

Tusks go through tree and come out on other
side. (First ed. †X1021.4.) *Wesselski Bebel II 137 No. 114.

Hog finds dynamite supply, eats it, walks behind mule; the
mule kicks the hog.

The explosion kills
the mule, blows down the barn, breaks windows out of house. The hog is ill for
several days. U.S.: *Baughman.

Lie: salesman guarantees sow to bear male, then female,
then kid.

(First ed. †X931.) Wienert FFC LVI 84 (ET 506), 104 (ST 167); Halm Aesop No.
11.

content:
Lie: venom of animal (snake, hornet, bee) causes object to
swell.
child: Snake strikes object, causing it to swell.
Rag so full of lice it can move.
Lie: man carried through air by geese.
The tragic death of the three gnats.

One of them meets his
death between the horns of two struggling oxen, another because of two restless
stallions, the third during a tussle between two giants. Lithuanian: Balys
Index No. 291* (†X1021.9).
Lie: cat scratches out bear‘s tongue.
Lie: crippled cat uses wooden leg to kill mice.

Eats the horses, is harnessed and runs in
the harness. (First ed. †X936.) *Type 1910.
Dog and other animal chase each other in hot weather.

Put back together but back legs point upwards. Canada, England, U.S.:
*Baughman.
Lie: greyhounds drag mill out of water.
Hawk flies away with geese on a line.

They have been tied
together as a protection. (First ed. †X912.) *Type 1876; BP III 337.

content: Lie: animal‘s food affects him in unusual way.

(E.g. Pine tops: milk good for cough syrup.) U.S.:
*Baughman.

child: Large mosquitoes fly off with kettle.

They have drilled through kettle. Their bills are clinched
inside like nails. U.S.: *Baughman.
Big mosquito with golden palace in his mouth.

Bumblebees imported to rout mosquitoes; the two insects
crossbreed and have stingers on both ends.

Insects eat team of horses or mules, pitch horseshoes to
see who gets what is left.

Liar says that in a certain place bees are
as big as sheep.--And the bee-hives?--The same as ours.--How do the bees get
in? (Various answers.) (First ed. †X1021.3.) BP II 515; *Wesselski Hodscha
Nasreddin II 219.
Cow wears church bell for cowbell.

Cow gives so much cream that several men do nothing but
skim cream.

Owner provides cow with green goggles, feeds her sawdust or
snow.
Lie: cow puts bread in oven.
Lie: ass with silver nose hunts hares.
Lie: goat carries one hundred cartloads of grease.

(Usually matched by tale of great pot to
put cabbage in.) (First ed. †X1024.1.) *Type 1960D; *Wesselski Hodscha
Nasreddin II 220 No. 454; Italian Novella: Rotunda.

content: Lie: man raises eggs from eggplant.

child:
(First ed. †X1025.1.) Hdwb. d. Märchens I
256a n. 18.

Lie: animals live inside great vegetable, usually feeding
from it.
Lie: hole from which great vegetable is removed.

content:
Lie: plants produce fruit in remarkably short time after
planting.

child:
Six short, fat husbands married to six tall, fat wives try
absurdly to kiss them at the threshold on their wedding day.

Fat man so unwieldly he fishes from his window in the
street.

Each of four stutterers thinks the others are ridiculing
him.

content: Man calls convention of all long noses.

Each member has mouth turned in a different way. Unavailing attempts to blow
out the light. U.S.: *Baughman; Danish: MS in Danske Folkemindesamling
(Grundtvig No. 166).

child: Deaf persons: search for the lost animal.

A inquires for his lost
animal.--B talks about his work and makes a gesture.--A follows the direction
of the gesture and happens to find the animals. He returns and offers an
injured animal to B in thanks. -- B thinks that he is blamed for injuring the
animals. Dispute. Taken to deaf judge. (Cf. †X111.14.) *Type 1698A; Aarne FFC
XX 16ff.; India: *Thompson-Balys.
Deaf peasant: travelers ask the way.

Travelers ask their direction. Peasant thinks they want to
buy oxen.--Peasant‘s wife arrives; thinks they say her food is too
salty.--Daughter-in-law and father-in-law misunderstand each other. *Type
1698B; Aarne FFC XX 28ff.; India: *Thompson-Balys.
Two persons believe each other deaf.

A trickster tells each
of two persons before they meet that the other is hard of hearing and must be
shouted at. A great shouting takes place, and each thinks the other out of his
wits. *Type 1698C; *Aarne FFC XX 29ff.; Wesselski Gonnella 118 No. 16;
Nouvelles Récréations No. 10; Nouvelles de Sens No. 4.

Lord: Good morning, Peter.--Peasant: I come from
Bingen.--L. What is the hog worth? --P. Two weeks from next Sunday (the wedding).--L.
Shall I come to the wedding?--P. Three and a half gulden. *Type 1698D; *Aarne
FFC XX 35ff.; *Pauli (ed. Bolte) No. 719.

Lord: Good day, Caspar. -- Caspar: I am making a reel.--L. Good day, Caspar.--C.
It is worth four pence. --L. Good day, Caspar.--C. Yes, my lord, whenever you
wish. Type 1698E; *Aarne FFC XX 38ff.
The deaf man and the proud nobleman.

A nobleman amuses himself at the expense of the deaf man.
Finally--Nobleman: I wish you a thousand gallows and ropes around your
neck.--Peasant: My lord, I wish you twice as many. Type 1698F; *Aarne FFC XX
39ff.
Misunderstood words lead to comic results.

In some the people are not really deaf but fail to catch a
word; in some they are deaf. Type 1698G; Aarne FFC XX 40, 76.--Spanish:
Espinosa Jr. No. 189; India: Thompson-Balys; Indonesia: DeVries’s list No. 296.
The deaf man with the bird in the tree.

A traveller asks the way and the man keeps telling him
about the bird he has caught. (The questions and answers often rhyme.) Type
1698H; Aarne FFC XX 41ff.

He plans the conversation with the expected answers. The answers turn
out otherwise.--A. How are you?--B. I am dead. --Thank God! What have you
eaten? -- Poison, I think.--I hope it agrees with you. *Type 1698I; Aarne FFC
XX 50ff.; India: Thompson-Balys.

-- “A
woodchopper.” The workman answers the traveler‘s courtesies with remarks about his work.
(Cf. †X111.8.) Type 1698J; Aarne FFC XX 51ff., cf. 67ff., 72, 75 (Types 12, 13,
16, 18).

The
youth answers unintelligibly but is praised nevertheless. Type 1698L.

The
drunken priest says, “In the morning I take a drink of rum and afterwards four
or five little drinks.” Type 1698M.
Deaf litigants and deaf judge misunderstand one another.

One asks name of town; another replies, “This is Wesley.”
Another says, “I thought it was Thursday.” Third says, “So am I; let’s have a
drink.” U.S.: Baughman.

content: Misunderstanding and quarrels in family of deaf.

Deaf husband orders deaf wife to prepare a certain dish:
misunderstanding.

child:
Audience of one hired to listen to egoistic dismal-voiced
singer.
Dwarf king falls into porridge-pot at court of human king.
Dwarf poet forced to swim in drinking-horn of human being.
Tiny ambassador put on horse with long stirrups.

Cannot say anything as he is too busy trying to keep his
seat. Italian Novella: Rotunda.
Short magistrate wears a high helmet.

Lame man taken on hunt in wheel chair beats the dogs home

content: Blind, lame, and deaf as witnesses in court.

Sees two plates where there are one, etc. Thinks two men are with her. Husband:
“See everything double except your husband.” Wesselski Hodscha Nasreddin II 186

child: The squint-eyed son and the bottle.

Sent by his father to get the only bottle of rare wine, he
sees two. Not wishing to show his father to be a liar, he breaks one--really
the only one. Chauvin II 196 No. 22.

content: One-eyed man as appraiser of horse.

Man asks bull if he is on the right road. Bull butts him and knocks him down.
